Asked the woman at a drive through how she was doing. She said no one ever asks. 

We chatted. Left her a $10 tip. 

She started crying. Said no one is ever nice to her at work and she feels alone. Husband is in the hospital and she’s scared. 

Just be nice to people. Never know what they are going through. Costs you nothing and can really add value to others. 

Very good risk reward.

full_text:
I quite like VSG so not going at him here. 

But in general, think people care way too much about buyback prices. For one, if they are too high you can sell into them. 

More importantly, Jensen allocated capital and effort (his primary job) that created more value in a shorter time than Buffett could have dreamed of. 

Buybacks are the last capital allocation decision. Sometimes I *feel* like value brain thinks they are the first decision. And sometimes I think value brain would be OK underinvesting in a business in order to buy shares. 

Of course, value brain would get slaughtered in that scenario. But then it would blame the Fed and not be introspective. 

*Send tweet*

full_text:
"The charts are dramatic, with the message practically jumping off this paper that equity investors should cheer loudly when Democrats are fully in the driver’s seat of the U.S. government and bond investors should cheer equally loudly when the U.S. has a Republican president with a split Congress. Not so fast. The underlying data shows the trends are not very robust.

 There are only three two-year periods with a Republican in the White House and a split Congress. Even though we’ve crunched almost 100 years of data to create the chart, which is a substantial time window, it seems perilous–or even reckless–to change an investment allocation based on just six of those years. A somewhat more robust conclusion would be to invest when the Democrats are in full control since there are 34 years of investment data under that setup, but we are not at all convinced that means we should dump our stocks and bonds when the Democrats are not in control."

-The Prudent Speculator (John Buckingham and Kovitz)
name: Bill Brewster

Here’s my pitch:

Personal: I talk to Alex daily. He’s very smart and a really great person. 

Professional: This book is very well organized. You’re getting it from someone who has spent **an enormous** amount of time thinking about Buffett and Munger. He took the time to group concepts/thoughts/threads.

Personal Part 2: Alex is the man and has a young child. Support him!!!

full_text:
I’ve always heard “if you’re not willing to buy it down 50% don’t buy it.”

I’ve come to think it might be better to say “if I’m not willing to buy it up 50% why buy it?”

I can already hear the top callers….

My point is there are situations where the stock can moon but the business improves much more. Those are the places to fish. Not when the business is getting shitty but the stock is “cheaper.”

Played golf today. Shit conditions. 20-30mph winds. Gusts 40+. 55-60 degrees. 

Played well most of the round. 5 bad swings. All resulted in doubles (and a triple). 

A reason I love golf is it’s like life. 

All about about avoiding the big mistakes. 

Lots of great shots. Ends up +13.
name: Bill Brewster

full_text:
I also love grinding through a round. It’s my meditation. 

That said I was mostly broken by 17.  Nature won. 

One of those bad swings was on 18. Two of them were after waiting while being cold. 

Need to be better refocusing.
